<p>Inmates in three Guatemalan prisons carried out apparently coordinated riots and took prison personnel hostage over the weekend, with officials reporting 46 guards and other staff being held. Guatemalan security forces moved to secure the perimeters of the facilities as the standoff unfolded. Authorities and media reports linked the unrest to gang influence inside the prison system and demands for improved conditions or privileges, underscoring the broader challenge Guatemala faces in maintaining control of crowded, violence-prone detention centers.</p><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>No negotiation: Interior Minister Marco Antonio Villeda said the government would not negotiate with the rioting inmates, signaling a hard-line response as security forces contained the situation.</li><li>Gang pressure: Officials attributed the takeover to gang members pressing for greater prison privileges, a dynamic that has repeatedly complicated efforts to restore order in Guatemala’s penitentiaries.</li><li>Workers held: Reports described the hostages as prison workers—guards and other staff—rather than other inmates, highlighting how quickly prison operations can be disrupted during coordinated disturbances.</li><li>Multi-site coordination: Authorities described the disturbances as coordinated across three facilities, suggesting planning and communication that can extend beyond a single prison.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Guatemala interior ministry: Officials said security forces secured the prison perimeters and the interior minister rejected negotiating with inmates during the standoff. (<a href='https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/guatemalan-inmates-riot-three-prisons-taking-46-people-hostage-2026-01-17/'>Reuters</a>)</li><li>Government officials (as cited): Officials blamed gang members for the incident and said the unrest reflected demands for greater privileges inside the prisons. (<a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/guatemalan-inmates-take-over-prisons-holding-46-people-hostage'>The Straits Times</a>)</li><li>Inmates (as described): Accounts of the riots said inmates were seeking better conditions, framing their actions as pressure for changes inside the facilities. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/1/18/guatemala-prisoners-take-workers-hostages-in-riots-across-three-facilities'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://japantoday.com/category/world/inmates-in-3-guatemalan-prisons-hold-dozens-of-guards-hostage'>Inmates in 3 Guatemalan prisons hold dozens of guards hostage</a> - japantoday.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/guatemalan-inmates-take-over-prisons-holding-46-people-hostage'>Guatemalan inmates take over prisons, holding 46 people hostage</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/1/18/guatemala-prisoners-take-workers-hostages-in-riots-across-three-facilities'>Guatemala prisoners take workers hostages in riots across three facilities</a> - aljazeera.com</li><li><a href='https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/guatemalan-inmates-riot-three-prisons-taking-46-people-hostage-2026-01-17/'>Coordinated riots erupt in three prisons in Guatemala, where inmates hold at least 46 officers and staff hostage as security forces secure the perimeters and the interior minister refuses to negotiate.</a> - reuters.com</li></ul>